The paper discusses probabilistic inference in Bayesian networks, which is a common topic in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The focus on reducing computation time through approximations and exploiting domain knowledge suggests a potential fit for data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) and signal processing (cs.SI). The use of likelihood ratios and joint probability distributions also suggests a potential fit for information theory (cs.IT).
